  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Daniel 5:24-28",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Daniel 5:24-28",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Then was part of the hand sent from him — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The LXX. read, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Δια τουτο εκ προσωπου αυτου απεσταλη αστραγαλος χειρος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "και την γραφην ταυτην ενεταξε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". “On this account hath the joint, or part of a hand, been sent from his presence, and hath formed this writing.” The reading in the Vulgate is to the same purpose. Houbigant translates the verse, “Therefore is the hand sent from him, the fingers whereof have formed this writing.” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And this is the writing, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "MENE, &c. — In the Arabic the three words are considered as participles, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Mensuratum, Appensum, Divisum, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "“Measured, Weighed, Divided.” The words are fully explained by Daniel in the following verses. MENE; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "God hath numbered thy kingdom,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " &c. — God hath numbered the days of thy reign, and put an end to it. The word MENE is doubled in the foregoing verse, to show that the thing was certain, and established by God, as Joseph tells Pharaoh in a like case, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 41:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". TEKEL; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou art weighed in the balances, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — The reason that an end is put to thy reign so soon is, that thou art found light in the scales of divine equity. Wicked men are often compared to silver adulterated, and alloyed with baser metals, which makes it too light when weighed in the balances: such was Belshazzar when weighed in the scales of divine justice. The same comparison is used by Homer, when Hector’s fatal day approaches, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Iliad, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "xxii, and by Virgil, at the death of Turnus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Æn. 12. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And so Milton, in the war of the angels,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "“ — — — — — Long time in even scale The battle hung.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "“ — — — — — Long time in even scale The battle hung.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Par. Lost, b. 6. 50:245.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Par. Lost, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "b. 6. 50:245.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
