  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 24.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Then was the part of the hand sent from him; and this writing was written",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As we have seen, the real equivalent of this verse in the Septuagint is a clause in ver. 17, \"And the hand which had written (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "γράφασα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") stood.\" If we take this to mean that the band now \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ceased",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to write,\" then the original text might be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "פְסִאָק יָדִא כְתָבָא",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the verb being written ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "fleaum",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in Mandaean manner. Then it would easily  happen that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "ק",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (in the older script  and ) was resolved into ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "ד",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (in the older script  and ). In support of this, it may be observed that while in the fifth verse the older construction of construct state and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "status emphalicus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is used to exhibit the genitival connection, in the present case the relative ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "די",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is used as a sign of the genitive. Starting with this, it is easy to see how the Massoretic text arose; but, on the other hand, it is difficult to see the sense of the reading of the Septuagint, unless this fiery hand is to be imagined as tracing and retracing the characters on the wall of the palace, and that the hand only ceased when Daniel stood before the inscription to read. Thec-dotion differs very little from the Massoretic text, and the Peshitta coincides with it. The word for \"writing,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "רְשִׁים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "resheem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is really \"engraving,\" and therefore peculiarly descriptive of the Assyrian mode of impressing on clay tablets or incising in stone the thing to be preserved. Daniel 5:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Daniel now turns to Belshazzar. The words: forasmuch as thou, i.e., since thou truly knowest all this, place it beyond a doubt that Belshazzar knew these incidents in the life of Nebuchadnezzar, and thus that he was his son, since his grandson (daughter's son) could scarcely at that time have been so old as that the forgetfulness of that divine judgment could have been charged against him as a sin. In the דּי קבל כּל, just because thou knowest it, there is implied that, notwithstanding his knowledge of the matter, he did not avoid that which heightened his culpability. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Daniel tells him how he had sinned against the God of heaven, viz., by desecrating (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 5:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
